s in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Great or Little Hampden (Bucks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Hamden","meanings":["English (Kent and Berkshire): habitational name from Hamden in Smarden, Kent, or from Great or Little Hampden in Buckinghamshire."]}]},{"name":"Baldwin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>bald</i> ‘bold, brave’ + <i>wine</i> ‘friend’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. In the Middle Ages it was a comparatively common name, which gave rise to a surname. It was borne by the Norman crusader  Baldwin  of Boulogne, who in  1100  was elected first king of Jerusalem, and by four further crusader kings of Jerusalem. It continued to be used by some families in England into the 17th century, but in modern times it normally represents a transferred use of the surname rather than a direct revival of the Norman given name."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Baldwin de Hampden was born about 1072, in Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Osbert de Hampden, was 34 and his mother, Mrs. Osbert de Hampden, was 36. He married Mrs. Baldwin de Hampden about 1097, in Buckinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"Abt 1072–":"umbes 1072–Surnud","1072–Male":"1072–Surnud","1075–Female":"1075–Surnud","1099–Male":"1099–Surnud","1040–1086":"1040–1086","1038–Female":"1038–Surnud","Abt 1097":"umbes 1097","1038":"1038","Abt 1099":"umbes 1099","1099":"1099","1086":"1086","1075":"1075","Abt 1072":"umbes 1072","1040":"1040","1072":"1072","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Hampden, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1072–":"noin 1072–Kuollut","1072–Male":"1072–Kuollut","1075–Female":"1075–Kuoll